==English==

===Noun===
'''gear'''
# equipment or paraphernalia, especially that used for an athletic endeavor.
# a wheel with grooves ([[tooth|teeth]]) engraved on the outer circumference, such that two such devices can interlock and convey motion from one to the other.
# a particular combination or choice of interlocking gears, such that a particular ''[[gear ratio]]'' is achieved.
===Verb===
'''to gear'''
# to fit with gears in order to achieve a desired ''gear ratio''.
# '''gear up''': to prepare for an activity.
===Interjection===
'''gear!'''
#(''mostly British (Scouse?)'') great or fantastic 


==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*jēra-'', from Indo-European ''*yōr-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[jer|jēr]], Old Saxon [[jar|jār]] (Dutch [[jaar]]), Old High German [[jar|jār]] (German [[Jahr]]), Old Norse [[ár]], Gothic [[𐌾𐌴𐍂]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[ὡρα]] ‘season’, Russian [[яра]], Lithuanian [[jore]] ‘springtime’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /jæ:aɹ/

